## Prompt Lifecycle & Naming

1. **Creation**: At the start of each new phase, create a prompt file in `docs/prompts/` (e.g. `PHASE_[N]_[DESCRIPTION].md` or `0001_[DESCRIPTION].md`) if it does not exist. **Always create the prompt before executing** — don't execute ad-hoc in a session (for cost and memory management).
2. **Sequence**: Use `PHASE_[N]_[DESCRIPTION].md` or a 4-digit sequence `0001_[DESCRIPTION].md`. Pick one convention per sprint and stick with it. Linear issue IDs remain the canonical source of truth.
3. **Completion**: When **all** tasks are implemented **and verified**, rename with `done__` prefix (e.g. `done__PHASE_01_INITIAL_SETUP.md`) and move to `docs/prompts/completed prompts/`.
4. **Location**: All execution prompts live in `docs/prompts/`. Never create prompts outside this folder.
5. **Handoff**: Every prompt must end with a "STOP" section naming the next file in the sequence (and the parallel sibling branch, if any — see STOP Protocol below).
6. **Git**: After completing a prompt (and renaming to `done__`), commit all changes and push to the remote on the current branch. Run `git branch --show-current` before committing to confirm you're on the intended branch.
7. **Issue-driven work (Linear / fix branches)**: Pushing the feature branch is **not** the end state. Before marking a Linear issue **Done**:
   - (a) PR merged to `master`
   - (b) Deploy executed (with explicit user approval — see [devops.mdc](devops.mdc) § Deployment Permission Gate)
   - (c) Post-deploy API contract check passes (see [devops.mdc](devops.mdc) § Post-deploy API Contract Verification)
   - (d) Playwright smoke (including CSS sanity — see [frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § CSS Sanity) passes, with screenshot captured
   - **"Merged to master" ≠ "issue done."** Skipping (b)–(d) is not permitted.
8. **Fresh chat for execution**: Do not run the prompt in the same Cursor conversation that created it — start a fresh chat to reduce context and cost.

## Prompt Content

- **Context**: Every prompt must reference [core.mdc](core.mdc) (and any other scoped rule the work touches).
- **Actionable**: Tasks must be concrete, file-specific, with code snippets where appropriate.
- **Verification**: Every prompt must include a "Verification" section with specific commands or checks (e.g. `curl`, `docker ps`, `npx playwright test`).
- **Self-contained**: Prompts must include **all** critical requirements from the source Linear issue — not just a reference link. If the issue specifies Magic Patterns integration, the prompt must include the full 4-step MP process ([frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § Magic Patterns). A prompt that says "see WEA-XX for details" without extracting the actionable requirements is **defective**.
- **AC parity**: The prompt's Verification checklist must cover **every** acceptance criterion from the source issue(s). Missing AC in the prompt = the executing agent will skip them. See [ac.mdc](ac.mdc).
- **Recommended model**: Every prompt must declare a recommended LLM model (see § Model Selection below). Before starting the prompt, verify the active model matches the recommendation.
- **Markers**: Print 💣 at the top and 💥 at the end (per [core.mdc](core.mdc) and [ac.mdc](ac.mdc)).

### Category-Aware Prompt Gate (HARD REQUIREMENT)

Before writing a prompt's Verification section, the prompt author **MUST** check whether the work touches any of the known bug categories in [`docs/standards/ISSUE_LOG.md`](../../docs/standards/ISSUE_LOG.md). If it does, the prompt **MUST** inline the matching prevention checklist from the relevant rule file into the Verification section. A prompt that touches a known category but omits the checklist is **defective**.

The Category-Binding Gate table lives in [ac.mdc](ac.mdc) § Category-Binding Gate — the same gate applies to both issues and prompts. The executing agent follows the prompt literally; if the checklist is missing from the prompt, it will be skipped.

## STOP Protocol

Every executing agent must run these steps before closing the chat:

1. **Open your PR** (if the phase requires one) — this is the completion signal.
2. **Read the sprint master** (e.g. `docs/prompts/PHASE_<N>_SPRINT_MASTER.md`) to find your phase row and identify the next prompt in the sequence.
3. **Check for a parallel sibling** (the `Parallel?` column in the Phase Summary table):
   - **No sibling** (`—`): output the next prompt name and model, done.
   - **Has sibling**: run the sibling PR check:
     ```bash
     gh pr list --repo spacemanspiff99/handbrake2resilio \
       --head <sibling-branch> --state open \
       --json number --jq '.[0].number'
     ```
   - **PR number returned** → sibling is done. Output:
     > ✅ ALL PARALLEL PHASES COMPLETE — start `<next-prompt>` in a fresh chat using **<model>**.
   - **Empty result** → sibling still running. Output:
     > ⏸ HOLDING — this phase is done (PR #NN open). `<sibling-branch>` has no PR yet.
     > When that PR opens, start `<next-prompt>` in a fresh chat using **<model>**.

**Why `gh pr list` and not a file check?** Parallel agents run on separate branches and cannot see each other's local file changes. A GitHub PR is the only shared, branch-independent completion signal.

## Micro-Task Principle

**One agent = one domain + one binary success condition.** Do not mix backend, frontend, and DevOps in a single agent invocation.

## Task Sizing

- **Max 3 tasks per agent.**
- **One verifiable exit condition per agent** — a single shell command or browser check that returns pass/fail.
- **Domain isolation**: Each agent touches one file tree (e.g. `api-gateway/` OR `ui-frontend/`, not both).

## Parallelism & Dependency

Independent agents (different file trees, no shared output) run in parallel. Document dependency order, e.g.:

```
backend fix agent + frontend fix agent (parallel)
  → build/integration agent
    → deploy + browser test agent
      → documentation update agent
```

## Micro-Task File Naming

When a phase is split into micro-tasks, use sub-letter suffixes: `PHASE_47A_BACKEND_FIX.md`, `PHASE_47B_FRONTEND_ARCHIVE.md`, etc. Each sub-file follows the same lifecycle (created → executed → `done__` → moved to `completed prompts/`).

## Automated Release + Multi-Session Discipline

- **Automation**: Let CI run lint/build/test on every PR; use GitHub **environment protection** with required reviewers for production deploy approval (see [devops.mdc](devops.mdc) § GitHub Actions Workflow Safety).
- **Sessions**: Do not implement, merge to `master`, and handle deploy in one chat. Use **three fresh chats** with pasted briefs:
  - **Session A** — implement + open PR
  - **Session B** — review CI, merge PR, verify integration
  - **Session C** — deploy approval + post-deploy verification (API contract + Playwright + screenshot)
- **Why**: Prevents context bleed (e.g. ticket closed while production unchanged) and keeps each agent within the [Micro-Task Principle](#micro-task-principle).

## Model Selection

Cursor has **two usage pools** — pick the right one to avoid burning API credits:

1. **Auto + Composer pool** — generous included usage, resets monthly, does NOT draw from the $20 API credit. **Use this for 90%+ of work.**
2. **API pool** — $20/mo on Pro ($70 on Pro+). Charged at each model's per-token rate. Reserve for tasks that specifically need a non-Composer model.

### Default: Composer 2 or Auto (Composer pool — no API cost)
Use **Composer 2** or **Auto** for all routine work. Composer 2 outperforms Claude Opus 4.6 on coding benchmarks (61.7% vs 58.0% Terminal-Bench 2.0) at a fraction of the cost, and it draws from the separate generous pool — not your $20 API credits.

### When you need a specific API-pool model

| Tier | Model | Input/1M | Output/1M | Use when |
|------|-------|----------|-----------|----------|
| **Budget** | GPT-5.4 Nano | $0.20 | $1.25 | Trivial edits, boilerplate generation |
| **Budget** | GPT-5.1 Codex Mini | $0.25 | $2.00 | Simple agentic coding tasks, 4× rate limits |
| **Budget** | Gemini 2.5 Flash | $0.30 | $2.50 | Best quality-per-dollar budget model |
| **Mid** | GPT-5.4 Mini | $0.75 | $4.50 | Moderate complexity, good reasoning |
| **Mid** | Claude 4.5 Haiku | $1.00 | $5.00 | Strong Anthropic reasoning at budget price |
| **Premium** | Gemini 3.1 Pro | $2.00 | $12.00 | Complex tasks, cheaper than Sonnet |
| **Premium** | Claude 4.6 Sonnet | $3.00 | $15.00 | Browser testing, cross-domain architecture |
| **Ultra** | Claude 4.6 Opus | $5.00 | $25.00 | Hardest architectural problems only |

### Agent-type mapping

| Agent type | Model | Reason |
|------------|-------|--------|
| File edits, migrations, archiving | **Composer 2 / Auto** | Generous pool, no API cost |
| Build checks, shell-only tasks | **Composer 2 / Auto** | Simple pass/fail, no API cost |
| Documentation updates | **Composer 2 / Auto** | Text only, low risk, no API cost |
| Multi-file backend/frontend fix | **Composer 2 / Auto** | Strong coding performance, no API cost |
| High-volume execution (many tokens) | **Gemini 2.5 Flash** | Cheapest quality API model ($0.30/$2.50) |
| Deploy + browser test (needs MCP) | **Claude 4.6 Sonnet** | Browser tool needs strong reasoning |
| Complex cross-domain architecture | **Gemini 3.1 Pro** or **Claude 4.6 Sonnet** | Deep reasoning, still cost-conscious |
| Hardest problems / last resort | **Claude 4.6 Opus** | Only when other models fail ($5/$25) |

### Subagent model (`Task` tool)
When spawning subagents via the Task tool, use `model: "fast"` for narrow, well-scoped tasks (file edits, shell commands, simple searches). Only omit the model parameter (inheriting the parent's model) when the subtask requires deeper reasoning.

### Cost discipline
- **Never use Claude 4.6 Opus as a default.** It costs 10× more than Composer 2 per output token and draws from the limited API pool.
- **Two-model strategy**: Use Composer 2 for execution (most tokens), escalate to a premium model only for planning/architecture decisions where reasoning quality matters.
- **Turn off on-demand usage** in Cursor billing settings to cap spend at your plan limit.
- **Before starting any issue**: verify the active model matches the `Recommended model` declared in the prompt.

## Cross-references (repeated for visibility — frequently skipped by prompt authors)

- **Category-binding in AC**: Every issue must inline the matching CAT checklist in its Acceptance Criteria — see [ac.mdc](ac.mdc) § Category-Binding Gate.
- **Magic Patterns instructions must be inlined**: A prompt that says "see issue for MP reference" is defective. The full 4-step MP process must appear in the prompt — see [frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § Magic Patterns.
- **"Merged to master" ≠ done**: Deploy + API contract check + Playwright CSS sanity must all pass before marking an issue Done — see § Prompt Lifecycle Completion above.
- **Playwright runs in Docker**, not on the host — see [frontend.mdc](frontend.mdc) § Playwright Containerization.
